</Table></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#3B3B3B><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub35.ezboard.com/unortherner.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Northerner</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#FF0000>(4/17/02 1:55:13 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub35.ezboard.com/fthesafehouseloungegeneraldiscussion.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=23334.topic&index=9>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://members.shaw.ca/sjgardner/Images/celeris2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Would anyone really object a DAoC skill system as AAXP?</span><hr size=1> Actually, the main problem with the DAoC system is that you were making irreversable decisions in a constantly changing environment.  Working out the 'best case' was pretty simple for many classes but you never knew what was going to happen in the future and you couldn't respec if things changed.<br>
<br>
I am not 100% happy with AA as it stands though.  Some classes get brand-new class-defining skills (Dire Charm, Endless Quiver and even Natural Durability for Warriors spring to mind, among many) while many classes are left after run3 wondering if they should even bother with many of their AA abilities. <p><center><b><font color=RED><a href=http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=78504>Celeris Tujimson</a><br>Blackguard of The Nameless<br>
